# YKDF udev rule: non-root access to the YubiKey HID interfaces.
#
# Layered mode (`ykdf init --layered` / `ykdf derive --layered`) reads HMAC-SHA1
# challenge-response from OTP slot 2 over the kernel `hidraw` interface. That
# node is root-only by default, so without this rule those commands need sudo (or
# the scdaemon transport, which still reads HMAC over hidraw). The default
# non-layered PIV path uses PC/SC (pcscd), not hidraw, and is unaffected.
#
# This grants the locally logged-in (seat) user access via systemd-logind /
# elogind's `uaccess` tag, matched by USB vendor 0x1050 (Yubico).
#
# We match the vendor only, NOT the USB interface number. Combining
# ATTRS{bInterfaceNumber} (which lives on the USB interface) with
# ATTRS{idVendor} (on the USB device above it) does not match: udev cannot
# resolve two ATTRS keys that live on different ancestors of a hidraw node
# (verified on a YubiKey 5: the OTP hidraw never got the tag until the interface
# match was dropped). Matching the vendor alone also covers the FIDO interface,
# but that already gets `uaccess` from systemd's fido_id rules, so this grants
# nothing new there.
#
# Install:
#   sudo install -m 0644 dist/udev/70-ykdf.rules /etc/udev/rules.d/70-ykdf.rules
#   sudo udevadm control --reload
# then REPLUG the YubiKey (or reboot) so the rule applies. Do not run a bare
# `udevadm trigger`: it re-enumerates every device and can disrupt other USB
# connections.

SUBSYSTEM=="hidraw", ATTRS{idVendor}=="1050", TAG+="uaccess"
